Helper Functions¶

In [352]:
def handle_na_values(df):
    '''
    This function handles na values in pandas dataframe
    which do not allow it to be converted into R dataframe.
    
    Input : pandas DataFrame
    
    Output : pandas DataFrame which can be loaded into R environment
    
    '''
    out_df = df.copy()
    for i in out_df.columns:
        if out_df[i].dtype == np.object:
            out_df[i] = out_df[i].astype(str)
    return out_df


def txt_into_df(path ):
    '''
    This function converts the txt file downloaded from
    "https://wonder.cdc.gov/controller/datarequest/D77"
    into pandas dataframe so that we can use it for 
    plotting purposes.
    
    Input  : path to downloaded text file from "https://wonder.cdc.gov/controller/datarequest/D77"
    
    Output : Pandas DataFrame
    '''

    with open(path) as f:
        l = f.read()
    l = l.split('\n')
    l = [i.split('\t') for i in l]
    len_ = len(l[0])
    l = [i for i in l if len(i)==len_]
    
    return pd.DataFrame(l[1:] , columns = l[0])

def color_func(value_in):
    '''
    This function makes the continuous columns of Age Adjusted Death 
    Rates into categorical column by using thresholds (10,20,30,40)
    
    Input: value in range (0 - Inf)
    
    Output : Any String value in the list ['1','2','3','4','5']
    
    '''
    if value_in>40:
        return '5'
    elif 30<value_in<=40:
        return '4'
    elif 20<value_in<=30:
        return '3'
    elif 10<value_in<=20:
        return '2'
    else:
        return '1'

state = txt_into_df('../input/state_2017.txt') 

state  = state.iloc[:-1] # last row is the aggregate deaths of all states which we don't need

state.columns = ["Notes", "State", "State Code", 'Deaths', 'Population',
       'Crude Rate', 'Age Adjusted Rate'] # fix the names of columns

state.State = state.State.apply(lambda x : x.split('"')[1]) # Convert '"CA"' into "CA" in State column
state['Age Adjusted Rate'] = state['Age Adjusted Rate'].astype(float) # convert "20" into 20 . str -> float

state = state[['State' , 'Age Adjusted Rate']] # we only need state and Age Adjusted Death Date

state.columns = ['state_name', 'AAR'] # rename Age Adjusted Rate column to short and sweet AAR abbrevation

state_df = state.copy() #making a copy so that we can experiment without modifying  state df
